vectorData.altText: 9. Identify the structural class of cell A. Be specific.

That's right! Multipolar neurons can be identified by the large, round nucleus and irregularly-shaped cell body. The irregular shape is caused by the axon or of dendrites extending from the cell body.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In this cross-section of the spinal cord, we have zoomed in on the grey matter to highlight the histological structure of the neuron. Specifically in the ventral horn of the spinal cord we see multipolar neurons (red arrow). They can be identified by their large pale nuclei.

In the midst of multipolar neurons, we see small dark stained supportive glial cells known as astrocytes (yellow arrow).
